<title>Fundamentals of Computational Neuroscience</title>
<course_type>Seminar</course_type>
<course_level code="O">For Undergraduates and Graduates</course_level>
<credit code="1">Half course</credit>
<enrollment_limit>12</enrollment_limit>
<meeting_text>Tu., 7-8:30 p.m.</meeting_text>
<faculty_text>Members of the Department</faculty_text>
<description>The brain is an extremely complex computing device. Computational neuroscience seeks to understand brain function by constructing mathematical models of the nervous system to summarize our knowledge and gain new insights into how neurons perform basic tasks, e.g., encode stimuli, form memories, or generate movements. This course presents computational techniques for investigating, modeling, and understanding the function of neurons, neuronal networks, and systems.</description>
<prerequisites>LS 1a, MCB 80, one of Math 19a/21a/21b or above, or permission of the instructor.</prerequisites>
